-- Aeroports de Paris, Cegid, Danone, GDF Suez, PPR: French Equity Preview
-- Adria Cimino
-- 2010-06-17T06:38:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-17/aeroports-de-paris-cegid-danone-gdf-suez-ppr-french-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose stocks may have unusual changes in Paris. Symbols are in
parentheses after company names and prices are from the last
close.  
 June futures on the CAC 40 Index slipped less than 0.1
percent to 3,673.5 at 8:36 a.m. in Paris. The CAC 40 climbed
14.42, or 0.4 percent, to 3,675.93 yesterday. The SBF 120 Index
increased 0.3 percent.  
 Aeroports de Paris SA  (ADP FP): The operator of the French
capital’s Charles de Gaulle and Roissy airports said traffic
rose 3.3 percent in May to 7.5 million passengers. The shares
fell 2.2 percent to 54.44 euros.  
 Cegid Group SA  (CGD FP): The developer of enterprise
business systems said it acquired human resources services group
Vedior Front RH for an undisclosed price. The shares rose less
than 0.1 percent to 21.52 euros.  
 Danone SA  (BN FP): Sales of the group’s Volvic water have
risen 9 percent in volume terms since the start of the year,
while Evian sales are 4 percent higher, Frederic Guichard, head
of Danone France’s still-water division, told Reuters in an
interview. The shares gained 0.3 percent to 44.23 euros.  
 Eiffage SA  (FGR FP): Eiffage and Macquarie Group Ltd.
confirmed the purchase of a stake in their APRR toll-road
venture. Earlier, Les Echos reported that the companies agreed
to pay 854 million euros ($1.05 billion) to raise their stake in
APRR to 95 percent from 81.48 percent. The stock lost 1.2
percent to 36.17 euros.  
 France Telecom SA  (FTE FP): The country’s largest phone
company can reach its aim of doubling sales in emerging markets
in three years, quicker than the announced timeframe of five
years, Chief Executive Officer  Stephane Richard  told Les Echos
in an interview. The stock slipped 0.3 percent to 15.50 euros.  
 GDF Suez  (GSZ FP): The operator of Europe’s largest
natural-gas grid signed a five-year, 4 billion-euro syndicated
loan to refinance credit lines due to mature in 2012. The shares
added 1.9 percent to 25.95 euros.  
 Ipsen SA  (IPN FP): The drugmaker said that its OBI-1
medicine for the treatment of hemophilia has received a positive
opinion from the European Medicine Agency’s Committee for Orphan
Medicinal Products. Final adoption of the opinion by the
European Commission is expected this year, Ipsen said. The stock
advanced 1 percent to 32.32 euros.  
 PPR SA  (PP FP): The owner of Conforama furniture stores
said it will take a minority stake in internet retailer myfab.
It didn’t give financial terms. The shares fell 0.2 percent to
102.20 euros.  
 Rhodia SA  (RHA FP): The French maker of plastics and
perfume ingredients is planning to acquire Feixiang Chemicals to
expand its presence in Asia. The price of the Chinese producer
of surfactants and amines is based on an enterprise value of
$489 million and the deal is expected to be completed in the
second half of 2010, the Paris-based company said. The stock
increased 1.4 percent to 14.37 euros.  
 Thales SA  (HO FP): The stock was rated “underweight” in
new coverage at HSBC Holdings Plc. The shares slid 1 percent to
28.47 euros.  
